  "prompt": "What are the most commonly used slangs?",
  "response": "Slang can vary widely by region, culture, and over time, but here are some of the most commonly used slangs in recent years, particularly in English-speaking countries:\n\n### General Slang\n1. **Lit** - Exciting or excellent; can refer to a party or event.\n2. **Vibe** - The atmosphere or feeling of a place or situation.\n3. **FOMO** - Fear of Missing Out; anxiety about missing out on something fun or interesting.\n4. **Ghosting** - Suddenly stopping all communication with someone, especially in dating.\n5. **Salty** - Bitter or upset about something.\n6. **Bet** - Can mean \"okay\" or \"yes,\" often used to agree with someone.\n7. **Flex** - To show off or flaunt something.\n8. **Tea** - Gossip or interesting information.\n9. **Bae** - A term of endearment for a significant other; stands for \"before anyone else.\"\n10. **Savage** - Acting in a ruthless, fearless, or cool manner.\n\n### Internet Slang\n1. **LOL** - Laughing out loud.\n2. **BRB** - Be right back.\n3. **DM** - Direct message, often on social media platforms.\n4. **SMH** - Shaking my head; used to express disbelief or disappointment.\n5. **ICYMI** - In case you missed it.\n6. **Lit AF** - Very exciting or excellent.\n7. **GOAT** - Greatest of All Time.\n8. **Cap/No Cap** - Cap means a lie or falsehood; no cap means truth.\n9. **Simp** - Someone who shows excessive sympathy and attention toward someone, often without reciprocation.\n10. **Woke** - Being aware of social injustices and issues, particularly related to race and inequality.\n\n### Youth Slang\n1. **Suss** - To suspect or figure something out; often means suspicious.\n2. **RIP** - Used humorously to denote that something is outdated or no longer relevant.\n3. **Slay** - To do something exceptionally well.\n4. **Drip** - Refers to style and fashion, especially if it's considered trendy or cool.\n5. **Cancel/cancel culture** - To stop supporting or endorsing someone or something, often due to perceived behavior.\n\n### Regional Slang\n1. **Crikey** (UK, Australia) - An expression of surprise or disbelief.\n2. **Y\u2019all** (Southern US) - A contraction of \"you all,\" referring to a group of people.\n3. **Bangers** (UK) - High-quality music or sausages.\n4. **Chuffed** (UK) - Very pleased or happy about something.\n5. **Fair dinkum** (Australia) - Genuine or real.\n\nSlang continuously evolves, so it can differ by community, age group, and cultural context.",
